    "breadcrumb": "Internship Report \u003e 3. Blogs Posted",
    "content": "In the era of data explosion, the ability to search and analyze information in real-time is no longer just an advantage but a vital condition for businesses. From industrial IoT sensors streaming millions of metrics per second, to e-commerce platforms needing to display products instantly, or security teams needing to detect threats in real-time—all require a powerful search platform.\nAmazon OpenSearch Service was created to solve exactly this problem.\nWhat is OpenSearch Service? This is a fully managed search and analytics service by AWS. Instead of worrying about infrastructure, you just focus on building your application. The Amazon OpenSearch Serverless version goes even further by automatically scaling resources according to demand without managing servers.\nCore Architecture Concepts Before diving into code, you need to grasp a few foundational concepts:\nDocument \u0026 Index: The basic data unit is a document (JSON format), organized into indices similar to tables in a database. Cluster \u0026 Node: OpenSearch operates on a distributed model. Master nodes manage the cluster, data nodes handle storage and queries, and coordinator nodes route requests to offload data nodes. Shard \u0026 Replica: An index is divided into shards (recommended 10–50 GB per shard) and replicated to ensure high availability. Inverted Index \u0026 BM25: Full-text search technology is powered by the inverted index structure and the BM25 ranking algorithm. Sample Application Architecture A complete search application on AWS is built using a multi-layered security model, with tightly coordinated components from the frontend to the data cluster.\nDetailed Workflow When a user interacts with the application, every request is processed through a clear sequence of steps:\nStep 1 - Access UI: The user opens the application via AWS App Runner, where the frontend is hosted and served automatically. Step 2 - Authentication: Amazon Cognito handles identity verification and authorization, ensuring only valid users can proceed. Step 3 - Route via API Gateway: All frontend requests pass through API Gateway - the single entry point for the entire system. API Gateway checks the token from Cognito and forwards the request to Lambda functions inside the VPC. Step 4 - Logic Processing at Lambda: Depending on the request type, AWS Lambda performs one of two tasks: indexing new data into OpenSearch, or executing search queries on the existing cluster. Step 5 - OpenSearch in Secure Zone: The entire OpenSearch cluster resides in the private subnet of the VPC, with no direct internet exposure - this is a critical security layer for sensitive data. Conclusion With the architecture above, you can build a production-ready search application on AWS without managing complex infrastructure. Amazon OpenSearch Service provides:\nFast and scalable search based on real business needs Built-in security and compliance without manual configuration Automated cluster management: AWS handles the heavy lifting, you focus on the product Flexible cost model: only pay for what you actually use The full source code and detailed deployment guide are available at GitHub - aws-samples/sample-for-amazon-opensearch-service-tutorials-101 - you can clone it and try it today.\nOriginal Article Link: Amazon OpenSearch Service 101: Create your first search application",
    "description": "In the era of data explosion, the ability to search and analyze information in real-time is no longer just an advantage but a vital condition for businesses. From industrial IoT sensors streaming millions of metrics per second, to e-commerce platforms needing to display products instantly, or security teams needing to detect threats in real-time—all require a powerful search platform.\nAmazon OpenSearch Service was created to solve exactly this problem.\nWhat is OpenSearch Service? This is a fully managed search and analytics service by AWS. Instead of worrying about infrastructure, you just focus on building your application. The Amazon OpenSearch Serverless version goes even further by automatically scaling resources according to demand without managing servers.",
